Below is a simple example using a web server configuration and a small application-level example. You can adapt depending on your stack.

---

## 1. Nginx: Deny All Access

If you control the web server, the cleanest way is via Nginx config:

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;

    # Deny all requests
    location / {
        deny all;
        return 403;
    }
}
```

Reload Nginx:

```bash
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

This will return HTTP 403 Forbidden for every request.

---

## 2. Apache (.htaccess): Deny All Access

In the site’s document root, create or edit `.htaccess`:

```apache
Order allow,deny
Deny from all
```

Or with modern syntax:

```apache
Require all denied
```

This denies all HTTP access to that directory (and subdirectories).

---

## 3. Node.js (Express): Deny All Requests

If you want to deny at the application level:

```js
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware to deny all access
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.status(403).send('Access denied');
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Service running on port 3000 (all access denied)');
});
```

Every route will return 403.

---

## 4. Conditional Denial (e.g., Maintenance Mode)

If you want to allow only certain IPs (e.g., admins) and deny everyone else:

```js
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const allowedIPs = ['123.45.67.89']; // replace with your IP(s)

app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const ip = req.ip.replace('::ffff:', ''); // normalize IPv4-mapped IPv6
  if (!allowedIPs.includes(ip)) {
    return res.status(403).send('Service temporarily unavailable');
  }
  next();
});

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Admin access only');
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Service running on port 3000 (restricted access)');
});
```

